    <title>Apple reveals new prices for iPhone battery replacements that go into effect January 1st</title>
    <content type="html">  
    &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/jvpdsMX3BXOAcy_KzIGKwdRmLvI=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/61376195/DSCF3201.0.0.jpg" /&gt;



  &lt;p id="09W646"&gt;Walking into your local Apple Store and getting a battery replacement for your iPhone is pretty cheap at the moment. Just $29. But when 2018 comes to a close, that temporary pricing — introduced in response to &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2017/12/28/16827248/apple-iphone-battery-replacement-price-slow-down-apology"&gt;last year’s throttling controversy&lt;/a&gt; that affected iPhones with aging batteries — will be going away. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="Sh6hq3"&gt;Ahead of that change, as &lt;a href="https://9to5mac.com/2018/09/12/apple-announces-new-iphone-battery-repair-prices-after-29-offer-ends-at-end-of-year/"&gt;noted by&lt;em&gt; 9to5Mac&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, Apple has &lt;a href="https://support.apple.com/iphone/repair/battery-power"&gt;updated its battery page&lt;/a&gt; with the new rates that will begin on January 1st. In 2019, out-of-warranty battery swaps will cost:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li id="hE8gcn"&gt;iPhone XS, XS Max, XR, X: $69&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li id="QOHxwK"&gt;iPhone 8, 8 Plus, 7, 7 Plus, 6S, 6S Plus, 6, 6 Plus, SE: $49&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li id="jxC7wq"&gt;All other eligible models: $79&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p id="YJsy1H"&gt;People with iPhones under warranty or covered by AppleCare+ won’t have to pay anything for battery replacements. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="XBTZVv"&gt;&lt;a href="https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT208387"&gt;Battery Health&lt;/a&gt;, a...&lt;/p&gt;
